<HEADLINE>
<P>
THOUSAND OAKS COUNCILMAN'S INCONSISTENCY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I am puzzled by the inconsistent views of Councilman Larry Horner regarding the 
need to maintain business character in Thousand Oaks versus the need to 
maintain residential character. 
</P>
<P>
He recently stated, "I'm going to be hard-nosed. . . . I'm not going to change 
the character of the business community because of advertising." 
</P>
<P>
Why, then, is he willing to change the character of residential neighborhoods 
because of rooming houses, which bring blight, traffic, drugs and crime? 
</P>
<P>
Horner's proposal, as chairman of the Code Enforcement Committee, will reduce 
residential zoning standards in violation of the city's ordinances that apply 
to occupancy levels, street parking, fire codes and infrastructure. His 
proposal does not solve the existing problems with illegal multiple rentals. In 
the name of "solving the overcrowding and enforcement problems," his proposal 
will increase density, increase street parking and encourage rooming houses to 
spring up in family neighborhoods. 
</P>
<P>
I hope homeowner associations and concerned citizens will not be deceived by 
slogans but will read the fine print. 
</P>
<P>
MARIE KOERNER 
</P>
<P>
Thousand Oaks 
</P>
</TEXT>
