<HEADLINE>
<P>
LIMITING SALES OF SPRAY PAINT TO CURB GRAFFITI 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Concerning the editorial regarding graffiti I would like to point out a few 
other people and organizations also working on this problem. 
</P>
<P>
We must congratulate Sen. Torres for his legislation. 
</P>
<P>
Locking up the cans is probably where it will go. Most of paint used for 
graffiti is stolen. 
</P>
<P>
There is another bill in the Legislature sponsored by Assemblyman Richard Katz 
(D-Sylmar) which will put a tax on spray paint and this revenue will be used 
for graffiti cleanup and educational work related to gangs. 
</P>
<P>
Many Los Angeles officials have worked together with VOICE over the past year 
on a major anti-graffiti campaign. Valley Organized in Community Efforts 
(VOICE) is a coalition of churches and synagogues in the San Fernando Valley. 
The City Council is proposing to lock up spray paint cans and use non-jail 
sentencing to clean up graffiti. 
</P>
<P>
Hopefully, all this work will come to fruition very soon. 
</P>
<P>
SANFORD DU ROFF 
</P>
<P>
Tarzana 
</P>
</TEXT>
