<HEADLINE>
<P>
ANSWERS FROM BABY DOOMERS ON WHETHER THEY'RE APATHETIC 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Why should it come as a surprise to anyone that America's youth are unlikely to 
comprehend much less take interest in public affairs ("Media Study Finds 'Age 
of Indifference,' " Part A, June 28). 
</P>
<P>
As a child of the eighties, I found the report less disheartening than comic. 
</P>
<P>
The very notion that today's youth -- unknowingly saddled with an economy in 
disarray, an ailing social welfare system, and an impending ecological disaster 
-- could fail "to find public events compelling" makes for a passable joke. 
</P>
<P>
What is really funny, though, is that older Americans -- having fed their 
children a steady diet of meaningless Hollywood fantasy, denied youth a proper 
education in favor of our "vital" defense budget, and left my generation with 
the likes of Arnold Schwarzenegger and Andrew Dice Clay for role models -- 
could ever express shock at the situation. Ha ha ha ha. 
</P>
<P>
PETER A. ZELLNER 
</P>
<P>
La Jolla 
</P>
</TEXT>
