<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUNTY IN BRIEF: LOS ANGELES; 
</P>
<P>
HONORS FOR PRIEST POSTPONED 2 MONTHS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Service Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A dinner in honor of Father Luis Olivares, the former pastor of Our Lady Queen 
of Angels Roman Catholic Church and a tireless crusader on behalf of Latino 
immigrants and refugees, has been postponed to Sept. 5. The event, chaired by 
Mayor Tom Bradley and union leader Cesar Chavez, originally was planned for 
earlier this month. 
</P>
<P>
It was postponed after Olivares fell ill and was diagnosed with AIDS. His 
doctors said he apparently contracted the disease from contaminated syringes 
while undergoing treatment for other maladies during his travels to Central 
America. Representatives of Los Angeles' religious, political and entertainment 
communities will host the event at Olvera Street Plaza near downtown as a 
tribute to Olivares and his work, said Linda Mitchell of United Way and one of 
the event's organizers. She added that the city of Los Angeles will declare 
Sept. 5 Father Olivares Day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
