<HEADLINE>
<P>
NORTH VERDICTS VOIDED BY U.S. APPEALS COURT; 
</P>
<P>
IRAN-CONTRA: ONE IS OVERTURNED. TWO OTHERS SET ASIDE UNTIL ISSUE OF MISUSE OF 
IMMUNIZED TESTIMONY IS RESOLVED. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ROBERT L. JACKSON and RONALD J. OSTROW, TIMES STAFF WRITERS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A U.S. appeals court Friday voided the three-count conviction of former White 
House aide Oliver L. North in the Iran-Contra scandal on grounds that his Fifth 
Amendment protection against self-incrimination may have been violated during 
the trial. 
</P>
<P>
A divided three-judge panel threw out North's conviction on one count involving 
removal of sensitive documents from the White House as the scandal broke in 
November, 1986. It said the trial judge had given erroneous instructions to 
jurors. 
</P>
<P>
On the two remaining counts of obstructing Congress and accepting an illegal 
gratuity, the panel set aside North's convictions pending a hearing by U.S. 
District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell on whether prosecutors made unfair use of 
North's immunized testimony before Congress. 
</P>
<P>
The appeals court ruling is a major setback for independent counsel Lawrence E. 
Walsh, who is expected to appeal. Walsh is supervising a continuing 
investigation of the role of top Ronald Reagan Administration officials in the 
sale of U.S. arms to Iran and the diversion of profits to assist the Contras in 
Nicaragua. 
</P>
<P>
In a 2-1 decision, the appeals judges said that Gesell had erred in failing to 
hold a hearing prior to North's trial on the potentially damaging impact of 
North's nationally televised testimony before Congress in July, 1987. 
</P>
<P>
North's lawyers had argued at the time that some members of Walsh's staff had 
been "tainted" by seeing or hearing some details of North's testimony despite a 
prohibition against using any of North's congressional testimony in his 
prosecution. They said some witnesses used by prosecutors had been similarly 
tainted. 
</P>
<P>
"The very purpose of the Fifth Amendment under these circumstances is to 
prevent the prosecutor" from becoming "the inquisitor, complete with that 
officer's most pernicious tool -- the power of the state to force a person to 
incriminate himself," the court said. 
</P>
<P>
For North, the immediate effect of the ruling is to remove the stigma of being 
a convicted felon. 
</P>
<P>
Walsh has the option of appealing Friday's ruling to the full appellate court 
or directly to the Supreme Court. He said in a statement that he was studying 
"the most appropriate next step." He has 45 days to make his decision. 
</P>
<P>
North already has completed three-fourths of the 1,200 hours of community 
service that Gesell imposed as his punishment. He was also fined $150,000, but 
Gesell had stayed the payment pending a decision on North's appeal of his 
conviction. 
</P>
<P>
North, in Baton Rouge, La., campaigning for a Republican Senate candidate, 
issued a statement through his attorney, Brendan V. Sullivan Jr., saying that 
he was "very grateful" for the court's action. 
</P>
<P>
"My family and I have been under virtual assault for more than 3 1/2 years in 
this extraordinary legal battle, and I hope that the independent counsel will 
end it now," North said. "I thank all those who have stood by us with their 
prayers and their support all these years." 
</P>
<P>
The ruling opens the door to eventual reinstatement of North's annual Marine 
pension of $23,100, which he lost on his conviction on May 4, 1989. 
</P>
<P>
A Navy spokesman said North would continue to be ineligible for pension 
benefits "until we have a chance to review the court of appeals decision." He 
said there was no obvious precedent on which to base a ruling. 
</P>
<P>
The two appellate court judges who voted to overturn the conviction -- David 
Sentelle and Laurence H. Silberman -- were appointed by Reagan. 
</P>
<P>
Chief Judge Patricia Wald, an appointee of former President Jimmy Carter, 
dissented, saying: "I am convinced that the essentials of a fair trial were 
accorded North, and that his conviction on the three counts of which the jury 
found him guilty should be affirmed." 
</P>
<P>
Legal authorities said that the recent conviction of John M. Poindexter, who, 
as Reagan's national security adviser, was North's superior, is not likely to 
benefit directly from the court's ruling because a much fuller hearing on 
possibly tainted evidence was conducted before his trial. 
</P>
<P>
However, Richard W. Beckler, Poindexter's lawyer, said he was "very pleased" by 
the ruling because congressional immunity "is a very big issue in our appeal." 
</P>
<P>
Walsh, in his statement, said that "our other ongoing investigations will 
continue." He was referring to a federal grand jury that has heard testimony 
from both North and Poindexter, who appeared under grants of immunity. 
</P>
<P>
Sources familiar with the inquiry said the panel was examining the roles of 
several other former Reagan Administration officials in the Iran-Contra case. 
They include Elliott Abrams, former assistant secretary of state for Latin 
America; Donald P. Gregg, now U.S. ambassador to South Korea, who was Vice 
President George Bush's national security adviser, and Alan D. Fiers, who was 
chief of the CIA's Central American task force. 
</P>
<P>
The appellate court, citing a possible unfair use of North's immunized 
testimony before Congress, said a 1972 Supreme Court decision prohibits federal 
prosecutors from making any use of such testimony against the criminal 
defendant who gave it. 
</P>
<P>
The court said that Gesell should have made a more searching inquiry before the 
trial when he learned that North's congressional testimony had served to 
refresh the memories of many witnesses who testified before the grand jury that 
indicted North in March, 1988. 
</P>
<P>
Such use of North's congressional testimony appeared to violate his Fifth 
Amendment rights and should have received more than the "truncated" review 
provided by Gesell, the appellate court ruled. 
</P>
<P>
The judges said they understood Gesell's reluctance to hold what he called at 
the time "a trial before the trial" on the issue of North's immunized 
testimony. But they declared that "the convenience of the government" in saving 
time should not outweigh a defendant's rights to avoid self-incrimination. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, COLOR, Former White House aide Oliver North at airport in Baton Rouge, 
La. Associated Press 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
UNITED STATES -- COURTS; APPEALS; NORTH, OLIVER L; TRIALS; SELF INCRIMINATION; 
FIFTH AMENDMENT; GOVERNMENT MISCONDUCT; UNITED STATES -- MILITARY AID -- 
NICARAGUA; UNITED STATES -- ARMED SALES -- IRAN; GESELL, GERHARD A; IMMUNITY 
(LEGAL); TESTIMONY; POINDEXTER, JOHN M 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA072190-0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 250322 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
